<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMPUTER FIRM REPORTS LOSING $6 MILLION IN YEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID OLMOS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
IRVINE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Computer Automation Inc. said Friday it lost $6 million in the fiscal year 
ended June 30, and the firm's chairman said the losses "have seriously affected 
the company's cash flow." 
</P>
<P>
The company, which manufactures automatic test equipment and minicomputers, 
said it also expects to report a loss for the first quarter of fiscal 1990, 
which ended Sept. 30. Computer Automation was late in reporting its year-end 
financial figures, but said results for the first quarter will be released 
shortly. 
</P>
<P>
The firm, which has been in financial straits for the past two years, said its 
revenue for fiscal 1989 fell to $6.4 million, down 10.6% from $7.1 million a 
year earlier. The loss for the recent year compares with a $1.3 million loss in 
the prior year. 
</P>
<P>
Computer Automation's efforts to raise badly needed cash were dealt a blow 
recently when a deal to sell its automatic test business to Technology 
Marketing Inc. of Irvine for $4.1 million fell through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Corporate Earnings 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
