<HEADLINE>
<P>
MALE MIDWIFE SAYS TOO MANY MEN MISSING OUT ON 'TERRIFIC' CAREER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from The Guardian 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite his mustache, Norman Taylor likes to think of himself as just one of 
the girls. But as one of only 12 or so practicing male midwives in Britain, out 
of an estimated 35,000, he is still a rarity. 
</P>
<P>
Taylor, 30, works in the delivery suite of the Princess Anne maternity hospital 
in Southampton. A midwife for five years, after eight years in general and 
psychiatric nursing, he has delivered nearly 200 babies and assisted in the 
births of many more. Confident and diplomatic, with a cheeky sense of humor, he 
chooses his words with care and is conscious of the fact that his sex gives him 
a voice often denied his female colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
Taylor admits that he has always liked children, but denies that there is 
anything special about male midwives. No unusual upbringing, flag-waving desire 
to break down stereotypes or superior qualities distinguish the men who choose 
to make a living helping babies into the world, he says. Instead, some women 
may mistakenly enter the "caring professions" because it is expected of them, 
rather than through genuine commitment. "Sensitivity and confidence are the 
qualities necessary for this job; it doesn't matter what sex midwives are as 
long as they really care about what they do." 
</P>
<P>
What attracted Taylor to the profession was the mix of psychological and 
physical care. "I've been run off my feet as a midwife, and women can sometimes 
be acutely ill in pregnancy, but for the most part pregnant women are well 
people who are going through a normal physiological process. You have more time 
than in general nursing to concentrate on parent education and physiological 
care," he says. 
</P>
<P>
Despite Taylor's insistence on being ordinary, there has been opposition to 
male midwifery since the first experimental schemes were set up in two London 
and Stirling hospitals in 1976. Men were finally allowed to train and practice 
on equal terms with women in September, 1983, but in six years the takeup has 
been slow and doubts persist. 
</P>
<P>
Ishbel Kargar, secretary of the 1,200-strong Assn. of Radical Midwives (ARM), 
which believes that midwives' traditional skills have been eroded by 
technological intervention and the decline in home births, says that some 
members regard male midwives with suspicion. "As an association we don't have a 
dogmatic view. But some members are violently against the whole idea and 
question the reasons for men wanting to get into midwifery. For some men it's a 
power trip. Midwifery and child-care have traditionally been women's field and 
men have only been involved in positions of power. Sex should not come into it 
because most men can be just as caring, but many of them use the qualification 
as a step on the promotion ladder." 
</P>
<P>
ARM allows men to become members, but the association's regional groups make 
their own rules and only two or three male midwives have joined. In one south 
London group they are banned, but this is partly because its meetings take 
place in a women's center. 
</P>
<P>
Some members have practical reservations about male midwives, as well as ones 
of principle. Kargar says that in times of worsening staff shortages, 
chaperoning -- whereby male midwives must be accompanied during procedures such 
as internal examinations -- can create problems. Women who might not wish to 
have a male midwife might also feel obliged to keep quiet for fear of being a 
nuisance in a busy ward, she says. 
</P>
<P>
Taylor, however, thinks that chaperoning can benefit patient and midwife. "If 
my integrity were questionable, I would not be employed as a midwife in the 
first place. But I have to be protected against accusations that may not have 
any grounds, and I believe it is preferable to have someone with you to comfort 
the patient. I never do a vaginal examination without first saying that this 
can be uncomfortable and undignified, but if you get distressed, then here is 
'X' to hold your hand." 
</P>
<P>
Taylor has sympathy with some of ARM's views, but thinks members can be too 
hard on men. "I believe that men can be feminists, too, and can have the 
interests of women at heart." 
</P>
<P>
Similarly, he feels that some radical midwives go too far on the issue of 
intervention-free childbirth. "I'm a supporter of natural childbirth and 
believe in women having choices, but you need to strike a balance. In an ideal 
world every baby would come out head first, face down, with no distress, but 
you get breeches, babies with growth retardation, large babies and small women 
-- the list is endless. Yes, be radical, but don't throw all caution to the 
wind." 
</P>
<P>
Despite the controversy, Taylor has never had much hassle over his choice of 
career. His parents and two sisters were "quietly proud" of his decision, and 
he expresses "enormous gratitude" to female colleagues, who have rarely created 
problems over his sex. 
</P>
<P>
Patients, too, after the initial surprise, have been supportive. Taylor fully 
respects the rights of women who, for religious or other reasons, may not wish 
to be attended by a male midwife. But on only one occasion has he had to 
withdraw tactfully from the delivery room, sensing that his presence was 
causing embarrassment. 
</P>
<P>
After five years in the job, Taylor says it is still "terrific" to witness the 
beginning of life. He regrets, however, that no other men have been through the 
system at Princess Anne during his time there, and believes they might be 
missing out. "I see no reason why men shouldn't become midwives, as long as 
they have the right qualities. After all, I'm living proof, aren't I?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
